The dorf formerly known as Merrahar...</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1919<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/27/03 6:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=87>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Socialized Medicine or Moral Obligation?</span><hr size=1> &quot;Once you're insured in the USA, aren't doctor's visits free also ? I don't know, I only go to the doctor when I need it, not because it is free. It isn't exactly fun.&quot;<br>
<br>
It depends on the insurance policy you have.  Paradoxically, the best insurance policies (and the most expensive ones) tend to not pay for doctor visits, whereas the less expensive ones do.  It has to do with the structure of the policy.  I guess the simplest answer is that the plans that most Americans have require them to pay a copay for each visit which is usualyl $5 or $10, then the rest is covered by the insurance company.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>- First, how do you define socialized and private med care ? Here in the Netherlands we can choose which company to get insurance from, but the government pays a large part of it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I would define socialized medicine as a single payer system.  In other words, the insurance is done by the government, not just funded by the government.  I would not consider a system by which the government subsidizes the purchase of private insurance to be socialized medicine, and such a system might avoid many of the problems associated with socialized medicine as it wouldn't remove competition.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>- About the hospitals in America. I've heard from government owned 'walk-in' clinics and that general hospitals are also government owned. What hospitals are most commonly used in the USA ?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It's highly variable.  The Roman Catholic Church is probably runs more hospitals in the US than any other signle organization, but I could be off on that.  Certainly it's true around where I live.  Many hospitals are owned and operated by universities/medical schools.  There are also many hospitals run by local governments.  As far as I know, there are no hospitals run by the federal government other than veteran's hospitals.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>- Is IVF covered in any insurance program in the USA ? It is gonna be removed from med care here in the Netherlands and I would imagine it would be pretty hard to get insurance for something like that.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
What is IVF?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>- Ammelen : In what is USA med care better than socialized med care ? In quality of the services itself (from a medical standpoint), better financially, better logistically ? And can you come up with specific numbers ? (again, not disputing it, just out of interest)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, the impressions I'm getting are based on a class on health care systems I took at Dartmouth as an undergrad.    The quality of services in the United States is better because there are fewer cost restriction measures and very cutting edge technology is used more often.  Also, the United States spends quite a bit more money on research than other countries.  Maybe I can dig up some notes from my class, but I remember that in comparing the systems, if you look at US versus other countries, most of the numbers look similar, or perhaps the US looks a bit worse.  However, if you drop out the uninsured, the US numbers are far superior to other countries.  This suggests that our system is the best in the world, but that we need to improve access to it for the segment of our population that is not insured.  The United States system costs more than any other system in the world as well.  The reason is primarily that we provide more comprehensive care.  It would cost even more within the confines of socialized medicine.  The other major reason the US healthcare system costs so much is the cost of lawsuits.  Americans will sue over everything.  It's estimated that about 10% of the cost of our medical system is directly related to lawsuits, and that doesn't include extra tests that are run by doctors to cover their asses.  Doctors actually run quite a few tests in the US that are not needed or indicated medically just to protect them from lawsuits.  This is a real problem in the US.<br>
<br>
