></strong><hr>the legal and administrative costs of that, together with malpractice insurance, is by far the biggest waste area in our healthcare system,<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
First of all, you can't group malpractice with administrative costs.  They're entirely different.  That's like saying military spending and peanut farming subsidies together constitute the largest part of our national budget.  It's not a relevant grouping.<br>
<br>
Changing to a socialized medical system would in itself have no effect on malpractice issues.  That's a separate issue that must be dealt with separately.  I agree it's a big problem though.  Personally, I think the way to change it is to make people who lose liable for the court costs incurred by the opposition.  That would give people some incentive not to press charges in weak cases.  This is a whole different issue though.<br>
<br>
The cost of basic care in the United States is actually less than it is in countries with socialized medicine (comparing the same service performed at the same level of quality in both countries).  The reason we spend so much more on medical care in terms of percentage of GDP etc is that the care we provide is so much better and we provide services not offered in socialized medical systems.  The inefficiencies of a non profit system would be massive.<br>
<br>
If you are right and a non profit medical system would be so much better, then one should be started.  It should compete with the profit based systems.  If it really is cheaper, people will choose it for their medical care as it will provide better care at a lower cost.  There is nothing stopping people from starting such a system.  What the ultra left radicals are asking is for us to create a non profit system and force everyone to pay into it because it cannot compete on its own.  If it could compete on its own, there would be no need to force people to join it.  If such a system offered superior care, I'd join it.<br>
<br>
Perhaps a one time government subsidy of such a program would be good.  Maybe it would just need a bit of a cash infusion to get it started, and maybe it could even pay it back later on.  I'm all for providing alternatives in the market, I just don't want the government forcing us into any single plan.<br>
<br>
Ammelen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=raolfcq>RaolfCQ</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1164<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/29/03 4:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=93>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Governmental insurance</span><hr size=1> Its the insurance companies, not the hospitals, that I was referring to.  I would think that was obvious when my whole paragraph dealth with the competition amoungst insurance companies to avoid payment, but I tend to give people too much credit I guess.  I also sort of thought this debate was about national health <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>insurance</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, which might also provide you with a contextual clue.  Anyone who has taken English 101 would be able to figure this out and save themselves embarrassment.<br>
<br>
Malpractice is a separate issue, I just felt it should be mentioned since I was trying to sum up what the biggest problems we have in medical costs.  They have little to do with the actual cost of high-quality, readily available care, as some would have you beleive. Competition between insurance companies to avoid claims, between insurance companies and thier clients and clients' employers for the same reasons, malpractice suits for ridiculous amounts of money, and the lawyers who feed off of all of it are all issues that could be fixed without effecting care quality one bit.  Its pretty obvious there is a symbiotic relationship between lawyers and insurance companies that has nothing to do with actual medicine. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1935<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/29/03 6:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=94>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Governmental insurance</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Its the insurance companies, not the hospitals, that I was referring to. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
What would give you the idea that I was talking about hospitals?  I was talking about insurance companies.  I was speaking about creating a non profit insurance company that would be able to compete, much like a credit union competes with banks.<br>
<br>
I think you are completely wrong in suggesting that socializing the payment system will not affect the quality of the healthcare system itself.  It most definitely will.  There will be less money available to pay for services, so the quality of services will decline.<br>
<br>
Ammelen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=amourbien>Amourbien</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 49<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/29/03 7:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=95>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Governmental insurance</span><hr size=1> About to go out so must keep this short...what if there were a socialist system of medicine (ie medicine for all) AND an insurance system whereby people that could afford to and wished for better care could get it if they bought it (much like is in place now)?  This would create a best of all worlds.  Everyone would have health care and those that wish extra special care can get it via insurance.<br>
