<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=514736&amp;resize=true" target="top">My Magelo Profile</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1936<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/30/03 1:05 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=96>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Governmental insurance</span><hr size=1> The only problem I would have with that is if the socialized system were required rather than optional.  Many families would not be able to afford private insurance if they had to pay into a socialized medical system.  The very rich would be fine either way, but the middle/lower classes would be hurt by that and would get lower quality care.<br>
<br>
I wouldn't mind a government run system that allowed people to participate if they chose to but didn't cost you anything if you didn't want to participate.  I have no problem with anything full optional.<br>
<br>
I would favor a system in which everyone got a voucher.  They could use it on a government or private insurance system, or if they didn't want coverage at all, they could take it in cash (exception here for children who would have to be enrolled in some system of health insurance).  The government could be sure to not price the coverage over the level of the voucher.  Private insurance companies would have to compete with the government, and vice versa, ensuring cost efficiency.  After all, whichever system were more efficient would be favored, and no one would be forced into something they didn't want.<br>
<br>
